In the next lemma, we state properties that we will need in the rest of the paper. 
\begin{lemma}
\label{lem-basic}
For discrete-time systems the pointwise stabilization radius satisfies  the following basic properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item[(i)] Homogeneity: For any compact set of matrices ${\cal{M}},$ $\forall \gamma >0,$ $\tilde \rho (\gamma {\cal{M}}) = \gamma \tilde \rho ({\cal{M}})$,
\item[(ii)] For any compact set of matrices ${\cal{M}},$ $\forall t \in {\mathbb N},$ $\tilde \rho ({\cal{M}}^t) = \tilde \rho ({\cal{M}})^t.$
\end{itemize}

For continuous-time systems the following counterpart of item~$(i)$ holds
\begin{itemize}
\item[(i$'$)] For any compact and convex set of matrices ${\cal{M}},$ $\forall \gamma\in{\mathbb R},$ $\tilde \rho ({\cal{M}}+\gamma \mathrm{Id}) = \gamma \tilde \rho ({\cal{M}})$, where ${\cal{M}}+\gamma \mathrm{Id}$ is the set of matrices of the form $M+\gamma \mathrm{Id}$ with $M\in{\cal{M}}$.
\end{itemize}
The same properties hold for $\tilde \rho'$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
In the discrete-time case it is easy to see that there is a bijection between trajectories of the system defined by ${\cal{M}}$ and the one defined by $\gamma {\cal{M}}$ (resp. ${\cal{M}}^t$) such that the number $\lambda$ in the definition of $\tilde\rho$  and $\tilde\rho'$ becomes $\gamma \lambda$ (resp.  $\lambda ^t$). Item $(i')$ can be proved in an analogous way.
\end{proof}

