\begin{proof}One can check that $\bar{A}_1^4=\mathrm{Id}$ (so that $\bar{A}_1^{-1}=\bar{A}_1^3$), $\bar{A}_2\bar{A}_1\bar{A}_2=\bar{A}_1$ (in particular $\bar{A}_2^{-1}=\bar{A}_1^3\bar{A}_2\bar{A}_1$), and these conditions imply that any product in $\tilde{{\cal{M}}}^t$ coincides with a product of the form $\bar{A}_1^{t_3}\bar{A}_2^{t_2}\bar{A}_1^{t_1}$  for some $ t_1,t_3\in \{0,1,2,3\}$ and $t_2\geq 0$ (and $t_1+t_2+t_3\leq t$). As a consequence of this fact it is easy to see that the corresponding switched system is not stabilizable, unless the initial point belongs to one of the principal axes. Indeed one has that  $|\bar{A}_1^{t_3}\bar{A}_2^{t_2}\bar{A}_1^{t_1}z_0|$ is either equal to $|\bar{A}_2^{t_2}z_0|$ or to $|\bar{A}_2^{t_2}\bar{A}_1z_0|$. If $z_0$ does not belong to the $x_1$ axis then the trajectory $t\mapsto \bar{A}_2^t z_0$ diverges and thus $|\bar{A}_2^{t_2}z_0|\geq C_0$ for any $t_2\geq 0$ where $C_0>0$ is a given constant depending on $z_0$. Similarly  if $z_0$ does not belong to the $x_2$ axis then the trajectory $t\mapsto \bar{A}_2^t \bar{A}_1z_0$ diverges and $|\bar{A}_2^{t_2}\bar{A}_1z_0|\geq C_0$ {\color{black}{for any $t\geq 0$,}} for some $C_0>0$.
